[
    {
        "content": "<p>I have some degree-5 univariate polynomial inequalities over the rationals (with coefficients with many digits of precision) that I want to prove hold over a particular interval <code>Icc 1 2</code>. My understanding is that polyrith used to do this, but is unavailable now. Is that right? Is there a standard alternative? It seems like grobner does equalities but not inequalities.</p>",
        "id": 564591765,
        "sender_full_name": "Geoffrey Irving",
        "timestamp": 1766103357
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You're right that polyrith is now unavailable -- somehow the sage server was overwhelmed (possibly with AI models spamming <code>polyrith</code> calls) so they shut it down. But I don't think it ever used to do inequalities; it was just powered by a groebner basis tactic to prove that elements of polynomial rings were in ideals i.e. to solve equalities in commutative ring theory. Does <code>grind</code> work? (by inequality I mean <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>≤</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\leq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span></span></span></span> not <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo mathvariant=\"normal\">≠</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\neq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mord vbox\"><span class=\"thinbox\"><span class=\"rlap\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"inner\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\"></span></span></span><span class=\"fix\"></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span></span></span></span></span>)</p>",
        "id": 564657965,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1766138500
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It should be possible to run polyrith with a local sage install instead</p>",
        "id": 564699909,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1766152155
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(and note that every call to <code>polyrith</code> also returned a <code>linear_combination X</code> suggestion which would work without the external call)</p>",
        "id": 564731206,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1766160535
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I tried <code>grind</code> with a simple inequality and no luck, alas:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pos</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Real</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">grind</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">—</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">No</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">luck</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 564813524,
        "sender_full_name": "Geoffrey Irving",
        "timestamp": 1766220371
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>grind</code> does not have support for non-linear real arithmetic reasoning. If <code>grind</code> ever manages to solve a non linear equation it's because some more abstract interpretation of the equation (e.g. interpreting <code>x^2</code> as a single variable <code>y</code> in a linear equation) is solvable using another <code>grind</code> facility.</p>",
        "id": 564823709,
        "sender_full_name": "Henrik Böving",
        "timestamp": 1766232289
    }
]